  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through various international organizations and agreements, aiming to create a unified approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering activities. Some of the key international efforts include:\n\n1. **United Nations (UN)**:\n   - **UN Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, focusing on the proceeds of drug trafficking.\n   - **UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): This convention includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **UN Convention Against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): This convention has specific articles targeting money laundering related to corruption.\n\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**:\n   - **FATF Recommendations**: The FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 to develop policies to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF Recommendations (also known as the 40 Recommendations) are widely recognized as the international standard in this area. They include measures related to legal systems, law enforcement, financial institutions, and international cooperation.\n   - **FATF\u2019s International Cooperation Review Group (ICRG)**: This group monitors the implementation of the FATF Recommendations and identifies jurisdictions with strategic deficiencies in their anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) regimes.\n\n3. **European Union (EU)**:\n   - **EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**: The EU has issued several directives to combat money laundering and terrorist financing within its member states. The most recent is the **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which strengthens the legal framework by expanding the scope of predicate offenses, increasing penalties, and enhancing the transparency of beneficial ownership.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - **Basel Committee\u2019s Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision**: These principles include guidelines for banks to prevent their services from being used for money laundering.\n\n5. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**:\n   - These institutions provide technical assistance and conduct assessments (through the **Financial Sector Assessment Program (FSAP)**) to help countries strengthen their AML/CFT frameworks.\n\n6. **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units**:\n   - This group facilitates international cooperation among financial intelligence units (FIUs) by providing a platform for the secure exchange of financial intelligence related to money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n7. **World Customs Organization (WCO)**:\n   - The WCO works to strengthen customs administrations\u2019 capacities to detect and prevent money laundering and terrorist financing through the movement of goods and cash across borders.\n\nThese international laws and frameworks are supplemented by national legislation and regulations that implement these standards into domestic law. Countries are encouraged to adopt and enforce these measures to ensure a coherent and effective global response to money laundering.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
